   "source": [
    "# Exercise 5 Solution"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "In this problemset you will apply your knowledge about the solution of ordinary differential equations. \n",
    "After the shock exercise using the particle based simulation of the COVID 19 spreading, this is an easy one. You should solve the so-called The Lotka-Volterra equations."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 1,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "import numpy as np\n",
    "from scipy.integrate import odeint\n",
    "import matplotlib.pyplot as plt\n",
    "from matplotlib import animation\n",
    "\n",
    "%config InlineBackend.figure_format = 'retina' \n",
    "\n",
    "plt.rcParams.update({'font.size': 12,\n",
    "                     'axes.titlesize': 20,\n",
    "                     'axes.labelsize': 18,\n",
    "                     'axes.labelpad': 14,\n",
    "                     'lines.linewidth': 1,\n",
    "                     'lines.markersize': 4,\n",
    "                     'xtick.labelsize' : 16,\n",
    "                     'ytick.labelsize' : 16,\n",
    "                     'xtick.top' : True,\n",
    "                     'xtick.direction' : 'in',\n",
    "                     'ytick.right' : True,\n",
    "                     'ytick.direction' : 'in',}) "
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {
    "tags": []
   },
   "source": [
    "**Lotka-Volterra Equation**"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Since we did already solve quiete some differential equations for mechanics problems during the lectures, we will use the Lotka-Volterra equations to do something new. These equations characterize the dynamics of biological systems in which a predator $y$ population and a prey $x$ population interact."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "The prey population is described by\n",
    "\n",
    "\\begin{equation}\n",
    "\\dot{x}=x(\\alpha-\\beta y)\n",
    "\\end{equation}\n",
    "\n",
    "where $\\alpha$ denotes the natural growth rate of the prey and $\\beta$ the death rate per encounter with the predator $y$.\n",
    "\n",
    "The\n",
    "\n",
    "\\begin{equation}\n",
    "\\dot{y}=-y(\\gamma-\\sigma x)\n",
    "\\end{equation}\n",
    "\n",
    "where the predators die naturally with a rate $\\gamma$ and grow with a rate $\\sigma$ if there is enough prey $x$."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "**Problem 1**"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Write a Python function that can be used with the `odeint` method of the `scipy` module."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 3,
   "metadata": {
    "nbgrader": {
     "grade": true,
     "grade_id": "cell-1f2e5a92448ca0ec",
     "locked": false,
     "points": 4,
     "schema_version": 3,
     "solution": true,
     "task": false
    }
   },
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "### BEGIN SOLUTION\n",
    "def LV(state,t):\n",
    "  x,y = state\n",
    "  xd = x*(alpha - beta*y)\n",
    "  yd = -y*(gamma - sigma*x)\n",
    "  return([xd,yd])\n",
    "### END SOLUTION"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Define some initial parameters where all of the rates are 0.1. Define a time vector."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 4,
   "metadata": {
    "nbgrader": {
     "grade": true,
     "grade_id": "cell-8606dcbee98e03c0",
     "locked": false,
     "points": 2,
     "schema_version": 3,
     "solution": true,
     "task": false
    }
   },
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "### BEGIN SOLUTION\n",
    "alpha = 0.1\n",
    "beta =  0.1\n",
    "sigma = 0.1\n",
    "gamma = 0.1\n",
    "time = np.arange(0,500,0.01)\n",
    "### END SOLUTION"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Calculate the solution of the Lotka-Volterra equations for equal initial population of both species."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 20,
   "metadata": {
    "nbgrader": {
     "grade": true,
     "grade_id": "cell-d2082148dd09e3fe",
     "locked": false,
     "points": 1,
     "schema_version": 3,
     "solution": true,
     "task": false
    }
   },
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "### BEGIN SOLUTION\n",
    "answer = odeint( LV, [1.5,1.5] , time )\n",
    "### END SOLUTION"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Plot the population of the two species as a function of time."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 21,
   "metadata": {
    "nbgrader": {
     "grade": true,
     "grade_id": "cell-6adfbdd3de5e6cd1",
     "locked": false,
     "points": 4,
     "schema_version": 3,
     "solution": true,
     "task": false
    }
   },
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "\n",

       "<Figure size 576x432 with 1 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {
      "image/png": {
       "height": 392,
       "width": 519
      },
      "needs_background": "light"
     },
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "### BEGIN SOLUTION\n",
    "fig=plt.figure(1, figsize = (8,6) )\n",
    "plt.plot(time, answer[:,0],label='prey')\n",
    "plt.plot(time, answer[:,1],label='predator')\n",
    "plt.xlabel('time', fontsize=16)\n",
    "plt.ylabel('population size',fontsize=16)\n",
    "plt.legend()\n",
    "plt.show()\n",
    "### END SOLUTION"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "**Lotka-Volterra phase-space plot**"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "The phase space plot is containing the variation of the number of predators with the number of prey. \n",
    "Plot the phase space."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 22,
   "metadata": {
    "nbgrader": {

   "source": [

    "plt.xlabel('prey')\n",

   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Calculate the mean population of the predators and the prey as a horizontal and vertical line. Add a plot of the solution for two other initial populations of predator and prey. Note if the mean population changes."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 11,
   "metadata": {
    "nbgrader": {
     "grade": true,
     "grade_id": "cell-2363b8f6a3377188",
     "locked": false,
     "points": 3,

    }
   },
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {

      ]
     },

  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "**Problem 2**"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "The next problem requires some exploration by yourself. You should explore the functions for calculating the Fast Fourier Transform of a time series as provided by the `numpy` module. Explore especially the meaning of the return values of the numpy.fft.fft function!\n",
    "\n",
    "Using the fast fourier transform method as described at the end of lecture 6, measure the frequency of oscillation of the population at various prey growth rates. Check again the functions\n",
    "\n",
    "~~~\n",
    "np.fft.fft\n",
    "np.fft.fftfreq\n",
    "np.fft.fftshift\n",
    "~~~\n",
    "\n",
    "Use all three to plot an appropriate frequency spectrum between the frequencies 0 and 0.1. Note that you should plot the amplitude at a certain frequency. Note that the result of the fft function, however, is in general complex!"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 13,
   "metadata": {
    "nbgrader": {
     "grade": true,
     "grade_id": "cell-85df6955b96c5ec6",
     "locked": false,
     "points": 3,
     "schema_version": 3,
     "solution": true,
     "task": false
    },
    "tags": []
   },
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "\n",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 432x288 with 1 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {
      "image/png": {
       "height": 287,
       "width": 438
      },
      "needs_background": "light"
     },
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "### BEGIN SOLUTION\n",
    "ft1=np.fft.fftshift(np.fft.fft(answer[:,0]))\n",
    "freq = np.fft.fftshift(np.fft.fftfreq(time.shape[-1],time[-1]/time.shape[-1]))\n",
    "plt.semilogy(freq[:1000],np.abs(ft1)[:1000],label='normal mode 1')\n",
    "plt.semilogy(freq,np.abs(ft1),label='normal mode 1')\n",
    "plt.xlabel('frequency')\n",
    "plt.ylabel('amplitude')\n",
    "plt.xlim(0,0.1)\n",
    "plt.show()\n",
    "### END SOLUTION"
   ]
  },
